e_gate.py`\\\\n+- `my-claw/tools/daemon.py`\\\\n+- `my-claw/tools/cypherclaw_daemon.py`\\\\n+\\\\n+## Correctness\\\\n+The implementation of R11 Call-Response Gating correctly transforms the follower's phrase shape based on the leader's realized performance. The logic in `_descend_from_apex` and `_fill` accurately reflects the requirements for complementarity and filling. Specifically:\\\\n+- When the leader is building (`is_building=True`), the follower's amplitude is reduced and its contour apex is inverted to complement the leader.\\\\n+- When the leader is pausing (`is_pausing=True`), the follower's amplitude is boosted and its contour apex is reinforced to fill the gap.\\\\n+- Role metadata (`leader`, `follower`, `solo`, `tacet`) is correctly parsed and respected, with the rule only applying to voices explicitly tagged as followers.\\\\n+\\\\n+## Completeness\\\\n+The task is complete according to the acceptance criteria:\\\\n+- `CallResponseRule` implemented in `render/rules/call_response.py`.\\\\n+- Correct transformations for building and pausing states.\\\\n+- Metadata role parsing covers all required keys and values.\\\\n+- Comprehensive test suite in `tests/test_call_response.py` verifies both functional behavior and role-based filtering.\\\\n+\\\\n+## Consistency\\\\n+The implementation is consistent with other \\\\\\\"Tier 1\\\\\\\" render rules in `src/cypherclaw/render/rules/` (e.g., `phrase_arch.py`, `articulation.py`). It uses the shared `Event` data model and follows the `role_is_eligible` contract established in `role_gate.py`. Although `PerformanceIntent` was mentioned in the spec, it is not yet present in the codebase (targeted for T-030), and the use of the `Event` model for these transformations is the correct adaptation for the current project state.\\\\n+\\\\n+## Security\\\\n+No security vulnerabilities or unsafe practices were introduced. The implementation consists of pure-function mathematical transformations on local data structures.\\\